n 2023 describing results from Cohort 1 of the THOR study.The study looked at whether a medication called erdafitinib was safe and effective at increasing the length of time that participants with a type of bladder and upper/lower tract cancer called urothelial cancer were alive compared to chemotherapy treatment. Participants had advanced or metastatic unresectable urothelial cancer with certain characteristics.Participants&#x2019; cancer must have certain genetic alterations in 1 or both of 2 related genes named fibroblast growth factor receptor 2 (<i>FGFR2</i>) and 3 (<i>FGFR3</i>).The cancer must have grown or spread after participants received 1 or 2 previous cancer treatments that included an immunotherapy medication.Additional effective treatment options are needed for people after immunotherapy.<b>What were the results of the study?</b> The median overall survival was 12.1 months for erdafitinib versus 7.8 months for chemotherapy. In the erdafitinib group, an estimated 85% of participants were still alive at 6 months and an estimated 51% were still alive after 12 months.The median progression-free survival was 5.6 months for participants treated with erdafitinib versus 2.7 months for those treated with chemotherapy.The objective response rate was 45.6% in the erdafitinib group and 11.5% in the chemotherapy group. Common side effects of erdafitinib were manageable and included high phosphate levels in the blood (hyperphosphatemia), diarrhea, an inflamed and sore mouth, and nail disorders.<b>What do the results of the study mean</b> The THOR Cohort 1 study found that treatment with erdafitinib extended the amount of time that participants were alive compared with chemotherapy treatment.After a pre-planned analysis determined that participants had better outcomes with erdafitinib, those receiving chemotherapy were allowed to switch to erdafitinib.Based on these results, erdafitinib was approved by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for adults with advanced or metastatic urothelial cancer with certain <i>FGFR3</i> gene alterations whose cancer continued to grow after at least 1 previous systemic treatment, including chemotherapy/immunotherapy.Erdafitinib is also approved in other countries to treat advanced or metastatic urothelial cancer; please check with your doctor for more details.[Box: see text].</AbstractText></OtherAbstract><CoiStatement>Yohann Loriot has received consulting fees from Janssen, Astellas Pharma, Roche, AstraZeneca, MSD Oncology, Clovis Oncology, Seattle Genetics, Gilead Sciences, Pfizer, Tahio, and Bristol Myers Squibb; and has been reimbursed for accommodations or expenses from Astellas Pharma, Janssen Oncology, Roche, AstraZeneca, MSD Oncology, Clovis Oncology, Seattle Genetics, and Bristol Myers Squibb, outside of the submitted work. Spyros Triantos, and Kris Deprince are employed by Janssen Research &amp; Development and have stock or stock options with Johnson &amp; Johnson. Arlene O. Siefker-Radtke received support from the National Institutes of Health, Michael and Sherry Sutton Fund for Urothelial Cancer, Janssen, Takeda, Bristol Myers Squibb, BioClin Therapeutics, Nektar, Merck Sharp &amp; Dohme, and Basilea; consulting fees from Janssen, Merck, National Comprehensive Cancer Network, Bristol Myers Squibb, AbbVie, Bicycle Therapeutics, AstraZeneca, Bavarian Nordic, Seattle Genetics, Nektar, Genentech, EMD Serono, Mirati Therapeutics, G1 Therapeutics, Gilead Sciences, Ideeya Biosciences, Immunomedics, Loxo, Taiho Oncology, and Basilea; and has patents planned, issued, or pending related to molecular testing in muscle-invasive bladder cancer, outside of the submitted work. The authors have no other relevant affiliations or financial involvement with any organization or entity with a financial interest in or financial conflict with the subject matter or materials discussed in the manuscript apart from those disclosed. Erdafitinib (JNJ-42756493) was discovered in collaboration with Astex Pharmaceuticals. Writing assistance was provided by Nicolisha Narainpersad, PhD, of Parexel, and was funded by Janssen Global Services, LLC. Patient reviewers on this PLSP have received honorarium from <i>Future Oncology</i> for their review work but have no other relevant financial relationships to disclose. Peer reviewers on this manuscript have no relevant financial or other relationships to disclose.</CoiStatement></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2025</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>20</Day><Hour>11</Hour><Minute>31</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2025</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>20</Day><Hour>11</Hour><Minute>31</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2025</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>20</Day><Hour>5</Hour><Minute>23</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pmc-release"><Year>2025</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>20</Day></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>ppublish</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">40539319</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC12218492</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1080/14796694.2025.2511589</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">40483179</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>07</Month><Day>16</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>07</Month><Day>21</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1938-0682</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>23</Volume><Issue>4</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Aug</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Clinical genitourinary cancer</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Clin Genitourin Cancer</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Erdafitinib versus Chemotherapy in Fibroblast Growth Factor Receptor-Altered Advanced or Metastatic Urothelial Cancer After Progression on Anti-programmed Death-(Ligand) 1 Therapy: An Exploratory Analysis of the Asian Subpopulation in the THOR Phase 3 Study.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>102376</StartPage><MedlinePgn>102376</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.clgc.2025.102376</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S1558-7673(25)00076-X</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="INTRODUCTION" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">The randomized phase 3 THOR study showed significantly longer survival with erdafitinib (pan-fibroblast growth factor receptor [FGFR] inhibitor) over chemotherapy in adults with FGFR-altered locally advanced or metastatic urothelial cancer (la/mUC) who had progressed during or after anti-programmed death-(ligand) 1 (anti-PD-[L]1) therapy (Cohort 1). This exploratory post-hoc analysis was conducted to evaluate the efficacy and safety of erdafitinib in the Asian subpopulation within THOR Cohort 1.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="PATIENTS AND METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Eligible patients were randomized in a 1:1 ratio to receive erdafitinib (8 mg once daily with pharmacodynamically guided up-titration to 9 mg) or chemotherapy (vinflunine or docetaxel once every 3 weeks). The primary endpoint was overall survival (OS).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Seventy-six patients were included in the Asian subpopulation: 37 were randomized to erdafitinib and 39 to docetaxel. The median follow-up for survival was 15.7 months. The median OS was longer with erdafitinib than chemotherapy (23.3 months vs.11.3 months; hazard ratio [HR], 0.47; 95% confidence interval [CI], 0.23-0.96). One patient (2.7%) in the erdafitinib arm and 5 patients (15.2%) in the chemotherapy arm had grade 3 or 4 treatment-related serious adverse events (SAEs). One patient (2.7%) in the erdafitinib arm and 4 patients (12.1%) in the chemotherapy arm discontinued treatment due to treatment-related AEs.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Erdafitinib showed improved survival compared with chemotherapy, with no new safety concerns in the Asian subpopulation. These findings were consistent with those for the overall study population in THOR Cohort 1 who received prior anti-PD-(L)1 therapy.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 The Author(s). Published by Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Matsubara</LastName><ForeName>Nobuaki</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, National Cancer Center Hospital East, Chiba, Japan. Electronic address: nmatsuba@east.ncc.go.jp.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Loriot</LastName><ForeName>Yohann</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Cancer Medicine, INSERM U981, Gustave Roussy, Universit&#xe9; Paris-Saclay, Villejuif, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Burgess</LastName><ForeName>Earle F</ForeName><Initials>EF</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Levine Cancer Institute, North Carolina, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Park</LastName><ForeName>Se Hoon</ForeName><Initials>SH</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Haematology-Oncology, Department of Medicine, Samsung Medical Center, Sungkyunkwan University School of Medicine, Seoul, South Korea.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Huddart</LastName><ForeName>Robert A</ForeName><Initials>RA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Levine Cancer Institute, North Carolina, USA; Division of Radiotherapy and Imaging, Institute of Cancer Research, London, UK; Royal Marsden NHS Foundation Trust, London, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastN